    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-03-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-03-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="421"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d421">
                <head>421. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VC_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJ_3">
                        Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d421fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1"
                            >Brzezinski</persName> Office File, Subject Chron File, Box 123,
                            <persName corresp="#p_VC_1">Vance</persName>, Miscellaneous
                        Communications 1/80–4/80. Secret. Carter initialed the top of the
                        memorandum.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-03-07">March 7, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Security Assistance for El Salvador</item>
                </list>
                <p>We have stopped all further action on the <gloss target="#t_MTT_1">MTT</gloss>
                    teams unless the necessary multinational effort can be assembled.</p>
                <p>You indicated that you had no objection to our sending riot control equipment to
                    El Salvador. We have in fact done this last November in the amount of
                    $212,000.</p>
                <p>This morning<note n="2" xml:id="d421fn2">Reference is to Carter’s March 7 foreign
                        policy breakfast that took place from 7:33 to 9:31 a.m. and was attended by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MWF_1">Mondale</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_VC_1">Vance</persName>, Brown, <persName corresp="#p_CLN_1"
                            >Cutler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JH_1">Jordan</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_DH_2">Donovan</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>. (Carter Library, Presidential
                        Materials, President’s Daily Diary) <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1"
                            >Brzezinski</persName> wrote to <persName corresp="#p_PR_1"
                            >Pastor</persName> in a March 7 memorandum: “We should help to restore
                        the Archbishop’s radio station. Perhaps <gloss target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss>
                        or <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss> can help. The <gloss
                            target="#t_MTT_1">MTT</gloss> is not to go into El Salvador unless other
                        Latin Americans go in with them. In the meantime, the Salvadorans can go to
                        Panama and meet with them, if that is helpful to the Salvadorans. Please
                        coordinate with State and Defense.” (Carter Library, National Security
                        Affairs, Staff Material, North/South, Pastor Files, Country Files, Box 21,
                        El Salvador: 3/1–15/80)</note> in our discussion of the <gloss
                        target="#t_MTT_1">MTT</gloss>’s we did not address in detail the question of
                    the military equipment ($4.5 million of <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">FMS</gloss>) we
                    were planning to send to El Salvador to help them combat infiltration of men and
                    equipment from other countries (principally across the Honduran border) and to
                    deal with mounting guerrilla action inside the country. I would appreciate a
                    clarification of your views on this aspect. The categories of equipment—mostly
                    communication and transportation—that we planned to send are the following:</p>
                <p>—radios</p>
                <p>—generators and power supplies</p>
                <p>—miscellaneous commo gear</p>
                <p>—ambulances and trucks</p>
                <p>—protection masks</p>
                <p>—night vision devices</p>
                <p>—bullet proof vests</p>
                <p>—hand grenades and grenade launchers</p>
                <pb facs="1118" n="1067" xml:id="pg_1067"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Recommendation:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>That we proceed with this equipment except for the hand grenades and grenade
                        launchers.<note n="3" xml:id="d421fn3">Carter indicated his approval.
                            <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName> returned the signed
                        and approved copy to <persName corresp="#p_VC_1">Vance</persName> under a
                        March 8 memorandum. (Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski
                        Material, Country File, Box 20, El Salvador: 3/80)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
